| And I suspect that you are overstating the importance of Tor in merely
| reading our forums, or the importance of anonymously visiting a forum
| without even registering or logging in. Plenty of anonymous proxies
| are used for that, and so long as no abusive activity is associated
| with them, no one cares. I'm sure some Tor nodes are still able to
| connect. If none of them are, the abuse problem is obviously aptly
| demonstrated. And it is not ours to solve or mitigate.
| 
| Our current firewall protects against the whole gamut of attacks,
| ranging from port scans to injection attacks to flooding to DDoS from
| a wide variery of suspect IP addresses. We prefer to have wholesale
| protection against abusive IPs over selectively disabled
| functionality, leaving us open to other attack vectors.
| 
| There's really nothing more to add to this. Our network, our rules, etc.

